      "properties": {
        "text": ""
      },
      "widgets_values": [
        "REFERENCE-OBJECT SCALE (tier 1) -- most reliable metric anchor\n\nHow to use:\n1. Load your photo above. Find a known-size object fully visible in frame\n   (a person of average height works well: person_175cm = 1.75m).\n2. Open the browser dev tools or just eyeball pixel coordinates from the\n   loaded image, and set AtlasReferenceScaleSolve's bbox_x0/y0/x1/y1 to\n   tightly enclose the object's full visible extent -- for an upright\n   object, y0 = top, y1 = base/ground contact point. This example uses\n   the cloaked figure standing on the ridge (top of head to boot soles).\n3. Queue. camera_height_m output shows the measured height; the corrected\n   solve feeds the viewport so you can sanity-check visually (hit Camera\n   View, the recovered geometry should look proportionally correct).\n\nCAUTION (found 2026-07-04, verified via direct testing): this tier is only\nas good as (a) your bbox precision, and (b) whether the object in the photo\nactually matches its assumed real-world size. For AI-GENERATED images\nspecifically, neither is guaranteed -- a generator has no metric constraint\nforcing 'this person is exactly 1.75m', so even a pixel-perfect bbox on a\nplausible-looking figure can still produce a wrong height if the AI rendered\nit at nonstandard proportions. This tier is most trustworthy on REAL\nphotographs of real objects with genuinely standard dimensions.\n\nAvailable reference_id options (see reference_data registry): person_175cm,\ndoor_210cm, sedan_car, city_bus, shipping_container_20ft/40ft,\nbasketball_hoop_rim, building_story_3m, building_3_story, building_25_story,\neiffel_tower_tip_330m, eiffel_tower_architectural_300m."
      ]
    }
